hands_on_practices.problem:
Let $(M,g)$ be an $n$-dimensional Riemannian manifold with Levi-Civita (LC) connection $
abla$, Laplace–Beltrami (LB) operator $\Delta := \operatorname{tr}_{g} 
abla^{2}$ acting on scalar functions, and Ricci curvature tensor $\operatorname{Ric}^{M}$. Let $f:(M,g)	o \mathbb{R}^{k}$ be a smooth harmonic map, meaning its tension field $	au(f):=\operatorname{tr}_{g} 
abla df$ vanishes identically. The energy density of $f$ is the scalar field $e(f):=	frac{1}{2}|df|^{2}$, where the norm is taken with respect to $g$ on the domain and the Euclidean metric on the target. Fix a point $p\in M$ and choose normal coordinates $(x^{1},\dots,x^{n})$ centered at $p$, so that $g_{ij}(p)=\delta_{ij}$ and $\Gamma^{\ell}_{ij}(p)=0$. Write the $\mathbb{R}^{k}$-valued components of $f$ as $f^{\alpha}$, for $\alpha=1,\dots,k$, and denote $f^{\alpha}_{i}:=
abla_{i} f^{\alpha}$ and $f^{\alpha}_{i;j}:=
abla_{j}
abla_{i} f^{\alpha}$, with indices $i,j=1,\dots,n$.

Starting only from the fundamental definitions above, the metric compatibility of the LC connection, the torsion-free property of the LC connection, and the curvature commutator identity for covariant derivatives on covectors (and their pullbacks), compute the coordinate expression at $p$ for the scalar quantity $	frac{1}{2}\Delta |df|^{2}$ in terms of the values of $f^{\alpha}_{i}$, $f^{\alpha}_{i;j}$, and $\operatorname{Ric}^{M}_{ij}$ at $p$. Then, explain why your expression is independent of the chosen normal coordinates at $p$ (i.e., is consistent with being a scalar built from invariant contractions). Your final answer must be a single closed-form analytic expression for $	frac{1}{2}\Delta |df|^{2}(p)$ in these coordinates.
